frameDefinitions: The words in this frame describe the death of a Protagonist.
A Person is in a state of prosperity and/or renown after some period of development or hardship in an Endeavor.
A particular Situation is likely (or unlikely) to result in a harmful event befalling an Asset.

The Means action by which a deprofiled agent (the Protagonist) has attempted to achieve a Goal, is finished and the actual outcome of the Means action has been resolved, so that it either specifically matches the Protagonist's intent (e.g. success) or does not match it (e.g. failure).
This frame contains nouns that refer to sensations in different modalities.

An Agent has attempted to achieve a Goal, and the actual outcome of the Agent's action has been resolved, so that it either specifically matches the Agent's intent (e.g. success) or does not match it (e.g. failure).
frameExamples: The machine was not switched off, but Mr. Lavelle <t>died</t> of natural causes, police said.
The huge sand dunes, perpetually changing, make for a surreal <t>sight</t>.
He <t>pulled</t> <t>off</t> his April Fool's Day prank by the barest of margins .
listRoleDefinitions: The role <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the being or entity that dies.  With verbs in this frame, the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the External Argument.
The role <fen>Time</fen> denotes when the dying or killing occurs.
The role <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the death takes place.
A sentient being or group of beings that is prosperous or well known after being involved in some <fen>Endeavor</fen>.
An event that the <fen>Person</fen> is involved in which leads to their state of prosperity or renown.
The time when the <fen>Entity</fen> is determined to be successful.
The <fen>Situation</fen> which may lead to a harmful event.
Something judged to be desirable or valuable which might be lost or damaged.
A concrete or abstract entity which may come to cause the loss of, or damage to the Asset.
The time period during which the <fen>Situation</fen> has the specified level of safety.
A particular location for which the <fen>Situation</fen> is safe. Frequently, it is to be inferred that the characteristics of the location make various <fen>Situation</fen>s safe or unsafe.
The action that the agent undertakes to achieve the <fen>Goal</fen>.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is what the agent attempts to achieve by performing the <fen>Means</fen> action.
An entity directed by the agent as part of the <fen>Means</fen> action in order to accomplish the <fen>Goal</fen>.
A participant function of an <fen>Instrument</fen> or <fen>Means</fen> in a particular event or in events of a particular kind.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the attempt succeeds or fails
The place where <fen>Means</fen> action succeeds or fails.
This role is only expressed with certain nouns in this frame, and then only with the help of a support verb, such as <ment>have</ment>:

This is the entity or phenomenon which gives rise to the sensation. In cases of veridical sensation, this role is not typically distinguished from <fen>Percept</fen>. Most of the phrases that express this role can be paraphrased as <ment>from</ment>-phrases, e.g.

The role <fen>Percept</fen> is used for phrases that express the characteristic property of a sensation. Typically this characteristic property is described with reference to the entity or phenomenon that produces the sensation---that  is why this role can be difficult to distinguish from Source. It is possible for Source and Percept to be expressed separately, however:

This role is assigned to phrases expressing the body part in which a sensation is located. Since touch is the least localized of sense modalities, words relating to haptic sensations are the ones most likely to occur with this FE:
This role is the perceptual background against which the Phenomenon is experienced by the Perceiver.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the sensation is perceived.
The <fen>Agent</fen> makes an attempt to achieve a <fen>Goal</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the attempt succeeds or fails.
The place where an attempt succeeds or fails.
listRoleExamples: <fex>The goldfish</fex> died.
Your father passed away <fex>about four minutes ago</fex>.
Your father passed away <fex>in his hospital bed</fex>.
<fex>He</fex> became a success at the age of 25.
Looking back, I had a very successful <fex>career</fex>.
After 20 years of hard work, he finally made it as an artist <fex>in '84</fex>.
Most people agree, <fex>going over 100mph</fex> is unsafe.
Honey is not safe <fex>for babies</fex>.
<fex>That man</fex> is a risk!
<fex>His daring, almost reckless, move</fex> succeeded and he lived to fight another day.

This move succeeded <fex>in securing trade concessions and the release of imprisoned
American sailors</fex>.
All of my usual source books seemed incomplete, but <fex>your website</fex> did the trick!
The machine was successful <fex>as a reconnaissance vehicle</fex>.
But it did the trick <fex>at the time</fex>.
A similar strategy, perhaps even bloodier, did the trick <fex>in El Salvador</fex>.
<fex>I</fex> have a tingling sensation in my hands.
The smell <fex>of the garlic</fex> made me hungry.
This herb gives off a smell <fex>of garlic</fex>.
I have a tingling feeling <fex>in my hands</fex>.
<fex>John</fex> managed a feeble smile.
<fex>On the bridge</fex> he succeeded in putting the wig on the corpse.
